<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the TWO `sys_choice` rows that
    enumerate the legal values of the `type` Choice field on the
    `x_[scope]_case` custom table inside the scoped application
    `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field    Type     Constraints
        type     Choice   General Inquiry, Complaint - extensible

    The values authored here are the AAP-mandated CLOSED enumeration for
    THIS POC build - exactly two records, no more and no fewer. The AAP
    Section 0.5.7 "extensible" note documents that future case types CAN
    be added in a subsequent build (e.g., Service Request, Audit,
    Investigation), but per the MINIMAL CHANGE CLAUSE in AAP Section 0.7.2
    no additional values are authored here without explicit AAP
    authorization, since each new case type would require:
        (a) a new `sys_choice` row in this file
        (b) a new Flow Designer flow in ../flows/ filtered by the new type
            (per AAP Section 0.4.3 Design Pattern: "two Flow Designer flows,
            one per case type")
        (c) updates to seed data, reports, and the portal submission widget
    Adding a third value here without parts (b) and (c) would leave the new
    type without a state-machine flow, breaking the AAP Section 0.7.3
    workflow validation gate.

    THIS CHOICE LIST IS THE DRIVER OF THE AAP'S MOST ARCHITECTURALLY
    SIGNIFICANT DESIGN PATTERN: two Flow Designer flows, one per case
    type. Per AAP Section 0.5.5 (state-machine), the trigger filter on
    each flow uses the EXACT label values declared below. If a label
    here changes, the flows MUST change too:
        ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            OnUpdate trigger filtered by `type = General Inquiry`
        ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
            OnUpdate trigger filtered by `type = Complaint`

    Per AAP Sections 0.5.5, 0.5.2, and 0.4.1, the labels declared here are
    additionally read by:

      The parent dictionary entry that declares this field as Choice:
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_type.xml
            (mandatory=true, choice=3 means "Choice list - dropdown only")

      The Manager View dashboard's "All cases by type" donut chart:
        ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml
            (donut grouped by type; with two values, two slices)

      The Experience Portal submission page (per AAP Section 0.4.4:
      "Page 1 - Case Submission: a simple form with five inputs (subject,
      type, description, requester_name, requester_email)") - anonymous
      requesters select one of these two case types via dropdown:
        ../portal/widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_submission_widget.xml
        ../portal/pages/sp_page_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
        ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
            (the scripted REST endpoint validates the inbound payload's
            `type` value against this Choice list before insert)

      The synthetic demo cases satisfying AAP Section 0.4.1 minimum-data
      threshold (each demo case picks one of these two values, with at
      least 4 General Inquiry cases and 4 Complaint cases distributed
      across the six statuses):
        ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_01.xml ... _demo_10.xml
            (per AAP Section 0.4.1: demo_01..06 are General Inquiry across
            all six statuses; demo_07..10 are Complaint across the four
            primary statuses)

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java line 134-135:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_type")
            private String caseType;
        ArkCase's `caseType` was a free-form `String` JPA column with NO
        platform-level enumeration check. Any caller could assign any
        arbitrary string. The legal values were not documented in code -
        ArkCase's actual implementations focused on FOIA-specific case
        types (e.g., FOIA Request, Privacy Request) that are explicitly
        OUT OF SCOPE per AAP Section 0.3.2. The ServiceNow target FIXES
        this by declaring a controlled vocabulary of EXACTLY two labels
        here, enforced at platform-validation time through the parent
        dictionary entry's `<choice>3</choice>` setting in
        ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_type.xml.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFileConstants.java does
        NOT declare a case-type enumeration; it only declares OBJECT_TYPE,
        EVENT_TYPE_*, and queue-action constants. The case-type enumeration
        was therefore implicit / undocumented in ArkCase - the target
        FIXES that defect by declaring the two values here explicitly.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - EXACTLY two records: no fewer, no more. Per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The two records below are the COMPLETE enumeration
        for this POC build. The "extensible" note is informational only
        and does NOT authorize adding values in this build.
      - Title Case labels: `General Inquiry`, `Complaint`. NOT uppercase
        (ArkCase legacy convention), NOT lowercase, NOT camelCase. The
        agent prompt's "Most common error point" warning specifically
        calls out: `General Inquiry` is TWO words separated by a SINGLE
        ASCII space - NOT `GeneralInquiry`, NOT `General-Inquiry`, NOT
        `general inquiry`, NOT `General  Inquiry` (double space).
      - Label = Value pattern: each `<value>` matches its sibling
        `<label>` byte-for-byte. The stored value IS the human-readable
        label - no integer codes, no enum ordinals, no separate
        machine-key. This matches the pattern used by sibling Choice
        lists in this app (sys_choice_case_status, sys_choice_case_task_status,
        sys_choice_case_priority, sys_choice_case_pending_reason,
        sys_choice_case_task_type, sys_choice_case_party_party_type) and
        is essential for the Flow Designer trigger filter equality check
        (`current.type == 'General Inquiry'`) to work without translation.
      - Sequence ordering matches the AAP Section 0.5.7 listing order
        ("General Inquiry, Complaint - extensible") in increments of 100:
            General Inquiry (100) -> Complaint (200)
        This drives:
            (a) the dropdown order on the case form
            (b) the slice order on the Manager View dashboard donut chart
                (../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml)
            (c) the dropdown order on the Experience Portal submission
                widget
            (d) the future extensibility - increment-of-100 spacing leaves
                room for inserting new values (e.g., Service Request at 150)
                without renumbering existing rows, though the AAP MINIMAL
                CHANGE CLAUSE prohibits adding any in this POC.
      - Both records are <inactive>false</inactive>: every value is
        active and selectable in the dropdown. There are no deprecated
        legacy values to filter out (this is a greenfield Choice list).
      - No <dependent_value/>: case type is a TOP-LEVEL classification
        whose legal values do NOT depend on `status`, `priority`, or any
        other field. The case type is selected at submission time and
        determines which Flow Designer flow handles the lifecycle, but
        there is no field whose dropdown options cascade from the type
        value at the form-rendering level.
      - No <hint/>: the labels are self-documenting (General Inquiry and
        Complaint are universally understood case-management terms). The
        agent prompt explicitly suppresses helper text per the POC scope.
      - No default value at this Choice level: per the parent dictionary
        entry ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_type.xml which has an empty
        <default_value/>, the user MUST explicitly pick one of these two
        values. Defaulting to either would skew dashboard analytics and
        bias user behavior - both internal users on the form and anonymous
        external requesters on the portal must make a deliberate choice.
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every record's `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` resolve into the `x_[scope]_case_management`
        scoped application by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope
        writes - the OOB tables sys_user, sys_user_group, sys_user_role,
        core_company, task, incident, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. Each
        record's `<sys_id>` element value is THIS record's own
        deterministic primary key - computed as MD5 of the canonical
        identifier `x_[scope]_case.type.<Value>` so that re-generation
        of this XML yields byte-identical output (no random UUIDs). The
        sys_id is NOT a reference to any other record. The MD5 inputs
        are documented adjacent to each record below for full traceability.
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time, which the import process resolves into the final
        scope namespace.
      - English language only: `<language>en</language>` on every record
        per the POC scope. The platform supports localization via
        additional sys_choice records keyed by `language`, but no
        non-English locales are in scope.
      - `<sys_domain>global</sys_domain>` on every record: domain
        separation is not used by this scoped application.
      - No PII: the labels are categorical classification terms only;
        no real names, email addresses, or organizational identifiers
        are derived from or stored in these records.
      - No smart quotes, no leading/trailing whitespace, no BOM. Strict
        XML conformance for ServiceNow Update Set re-import preview.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_[scope]_case_management.xml (scoped application)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml (scope record)
        - ../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml (parent table; type field's host)
        - ../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_type.xml (parent dictionary entry;
          declares the column shape, choice=3, mandatory=true. Without
          this entry the sys_choice records below have no column to
          attach to.)

      THIS RECORD SET MUST LOAD BEFORE:
        - ../flows/general_inquiry_state_machine.xml
            (OnUpdate trigger filtered by `type = General Inquiry`)
        - ../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml
            (OnUpdate trigger filtered by `type = Complaint`)
        - ../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml
            (donut chart grouped by type - two slices)
        - ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
            (anonymous portal submission validates inbound `type` against
            this Choice list before insert)
        - ../portal/widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_submission_widget.xml
            (the portal submission widget displays a dropdown of these
            choices to anonymous external requesters)
        - ../portal/pages/sp_page_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
            (the page that hosts the submission widget)
        - ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml
            (demo cases set this field; values must match the labels here
            byte-for-byte for the GlideRecord seed lookups by `number` to
            populate the type field correctly)

      Loading order is enforced by the alphabetical Update Set preview
      ordering plus the record-by-record dependency-resolution pass.

    The MD5 input for each record's <sys_id> is the canonical identifier
    <table>.<element>.<value>:
        MD5("x_[scope]_case.type.General Inquiry") = 3e7609e334c65bf732756bc25d9f21c2
        MD5("x_[scope]_case.type.Complaint")       = 82d6b899a325f343095766a013d6255e
    These hashes are recomputable from the AAP-mandated canonical input,
    guaranteeing deterministic XML re-generation across all build runs.
-->
<unload unload_date="2025-01-01 00:00:00">
<sys_choice action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
    <dependent_value/>
    <element>type</element>
    <hint/>
    <inactive>false</inactive>
    <label>General Inquiry</label>
    <language>en</language>
    <name>x_[scope]_case</name>
    <sequence>100</sequence>
    <sys_class_name>sys_choice</sys_class_name>
    <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
    <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
    <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
    <sys_id>3e7609e334c65bf732756bc25d9f21c2</sys_id>
    <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
    <sys_overrides/>
    <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]_case_management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_package>
    <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_scope>
    <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
    <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
    <value>General Inquiry</value>
</sys_choice>
<sys_choice action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
    <dependent_value/>
    <element>type</element>
    <hint/>
    <inactive>false</inactive>
    <label>Complaint</label>
    <language>en</language>
    <name>x_[scope]_case</name>
    <sequence>200</sequence>
    <sys_class_name>sys_choice</sys_class_name>
    <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
    <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
    <sys_domain>global</sys_domain>
    <sys_id>82d6b899a325f343095766a013d6255e</sys_id>
    <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
    <sys_overrides/>
    <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]_case_management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_package>
    <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]_case_management</sys_scope>
    <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
    <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
    <value>Complaint</value>
</sys_choice>
</unload>
